Goal

The goal is to produce the figures for the BXD mapping paper.

Figures

Figure 1: Including genomic variants in inbred mouse transcriptome read mapping overview.

Figure 1 | Including genomic variants in inbred mouse transcriptome read mapping overview.

  1. BXD mouse recombinant inbred panel. Samples come from mice that are: BXD advanced recombinant inbred lines, parental inbred strains which are C57BL/6J (B6) and DBA/2J (D2), and not inbred first generation cross between the parental strains (F1).
  2. RNA-seq read mapping strategies in this study.
  3. BXD genotypes available from GeneNetwork and D2-specific genomic variants available from dbSNP.
  4. Genotypes imputation workflow. B6 regions or alleles are in black, D2 regions or alleles are in brown.

Figure 2: Two parental assemblies strategy.

Figure 2 | Two parental assemblies strategy.

  1. Mappability of all samples on 2 parental assemblies (samples are mapped on GRCm38: black symbols and on D2 assembly: brown symbols) using permissive mapping setting (STAR default) in cortex (left) and liver (right).
  2. Mappability of parental and F1 (BxD and DxB) samples on 2 parental assemblies using restrictive mapping setting allowing 0 mismatches. Same legend than in A.
  3. Mappability of parental and F1 samples on 2 parental assemblies using restrictive mapping setting but allowing up to 10 mismatches. Same legend than in A.
  4. Differential mapping (DM) analysis of D2 assembly compared to GRCm38 in the cortex (left) or in the liver (right). Genes are classified as DM genes if FDR adjusted p-value < 0.05 (red) or non DM genes otherwise (black).

Figure 3: Line-specific references strategy.

For GRCm38 vs D2 assembly, 38% of genes are significantly (below or equal to 0.05) differentially mapped in cortex, and 22% in liver.

For GRCm38 vs BXD-specific, 2% of genes are significantly (below or equal to 0.05) differentially mapped in cortex, and 2% in liver.

Figure 3 | Line-specific references strategy.

  1. Relative mappability of customized D2-specific reference (GRCm38 modified with D2-specific indels and SNVs from dbSNP) compared to GRCm38 on parental and F1 samples with exact matches. Samples are all NSD. Colors indicate genetic of the samples: B6 (black), D2 (light brown), and F1 (white) between B6 and D2 strains. The F1 samples are BxD if the mother is B6 and the father is D2 (as for the BXD lines), or the reverse for DxB.
  2. Differential mapping (DM) analysis of customized BXD specific references compared to GRCm38, in the cortex (left) or in the liver (right). Genes are classified as DM genes if FDR adjusted p-value < 0.05 (red) or non DM genes otherwise (black).
  3. Relative mappability of BXD-specific references (GRCm38 modified for each BXD line with GeneNetwork genotypes and imputed variants) compared to GRCm38 on BXD samples with exact matches.

Figure 4: Consequences of mapping reference at local eQTL level.

Figure 4 | Consequences of mapping reference at local eQTL level.

  1. Percentage of significant (FDR 5%) local eQTLs with GRCm38 or BXD-specific references.
  2. Percentage of skewness of significant(FDR 5%) local eQTLs slope with GRCm38 or BXD-specific references.
  3. Local eQTLs overlapping between GRCm38 and BXD-specific references in cortex NSD (left) or in liver NSD (right). The sign of the slope measures the direction of gene expression (B6 or D2 as more expressed allele).

Figure 5: Evaluating mapping parameters.

Figure 5 | Evaluating mapping parameters.

  1. The performance on local eQTLs of selected mapping settings on cortex samples (average between NSD and SD conditions) is measured by the percentage of expressed genes than have a significant local eQTLs.
  2. The performance on local eQTLs of selected mapping settings on liver samples (average between NSD and SD conditions) is measured by the percentage of expressed genes than have a significant local eQTLs.
